'''Oligodactyly'''  (from Greek prefix oligo-, "having few, having little" + δάκτυλος (daktulos) "finger") in [[human]]s is "the presence of fewer than five fingers or toes on a hand or foot".<ref>[http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/glossary=oligodactyly NIH website], citing ''Merriam-Webster's Medical Dictionary''.  Accessed February 16, 2010.</ref><ref name="MedTerm">[http://www.medterms.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=6668 Medical terms Dictionary].  Accessed February 16, 2010</ref> It is quite often incorrectly called ''hypodactyly'', but the [[Greek (language)|Greek]] prefixes [[wiktionary:hypo-|hypo-]] and [[wiktionary:hyper-|hyper-]] are used for [[wiktionary:continuous|continuous]] scales (e.g. in [[hypoglycaemia]] and [[hypercholesterolemia]]). This as opposed to [[wiktionary:discrete|discrete]] or [[wiktionary:countable|countable]] scales, where [[wiktionary:oligo-|oligo-]] and [[wiktionary:poly-|poly-]] should be used (e.g. in [[oligarchy]] and [[polygamy]]). Oligodactyly is therefore the opposite of [[polydactyly]].<ref name="MedTerm" /><ref name=Journal>[http://www.journals.elsevierhealth.com/periodicals/yjssh/article/PIIS1531091402500206/abstract]. Accessed February 16, 2010.</ref> Very rare, this medical condition usually has a [[Genetics|genetic]] or familial [[etiology]].<ref name=Journal /><ref name = "Jones">
